🎯 Polished Interview Version (Professional & Tight)
Here’s how you could say this confidently in an interview:
I worked in psychiatry and responded to an emergency behavioral situation where a large patient became highly agitated and confrontational. Over a dozen staff members responded, and we needed to decide who would approach him in order to de-escalate the situation safely. I was selected to lead the interaction.
The patient was verbally aggressive and challenged my authority, even telling me I was “at the bottom of the totem pole.” Instead of reacting defensively, I acknowledged his statement calmly and used humility and respect to build rapport. I reassured him that our priority was his safety and ours, and that we simply wanted to help him receive the medication his doctor ordered.
By keeping the tone respectful and non-confrontational, he agreed to cooperate. The nurse was able to administer the injection safely without restraints or injury.
That experience reinforced for me how powerful calm communication and emotional control are in high-pressure situations.




⭐ Question 3 (Accountability / Ownership)
Tell me about a time you made a mistake. What happened and what did you learn from it?
Situation: I was in the medical clinic and we had a patient that we needed to be seen by the doctor
Task : We roomed the patient and started to take their vital signs. 
When we told the doctor the patient was ready, I realized that we had the wrong patient
We had already charted vital signs on to the wrong patient. 
Action : We got the correct patient and took vital signs and the patient saw the doctor.
We had asked the patient if that was their name and they said yes. 
But we needed to ask a 2nd identifier to make sure. 
Results : They began implementing name tags but I also began to ask 2 identifying questions
To make sure we have the correct patient. 

Luis — this is a very strong accountability story.
A lot of people struggle with “tell me about a mistake” because they either:
Pick something too small (looks fake), or


Pick something too big (looks unsafe)


Yours is solid because:
It’s real


It involves patient safety


You corrected it


You changed your behavior afterward


That’s exactly what interviewers want.

